You're right. At the end of the day, `test_crate()` is just building up a `cargo test` command with computed arguments. The complexity is in *figuring out* what args to pass (spec loading, nightly detection, etc.), not in doing something other than running cargo.

So `TestCmd` could implement `CargoPassthrough` with a custom `execute()` that:
1. Loads spec
2. Generates build.rs if needed
3. Builds the cargo command with computed args
4. Runs it
5. Cleans up build.rs

```rust
#[derive(Args)]
pub struct TestCmd {
    #[arg(short = 'p', long = "package")]
    pub package: Option<String>,
    #[arg(short = 'a', long = "all")]
    pub all: bool,
    #[arg(short = 't', long = "tspec")]
    pub tspec: Option<String>,
    #[arg(short, long)]
    pub release: bool,
    #[arg(short, long)]
    pub fail_fast: bool,
}

impl CargoPassthrough for TestCmd {
    fn subcommand(&self) -> &str { "test" }

    fn args(&self) -> Vec<OsString> { 
        vec![]  // Not used - execute() builds its own
    }

    fn execute(&self, project_root: &Path) -> Result<ExitCode> {
        // Full logic from test_crate() + test_all()
    }
}
```

